content.text:
[
  {
    "ruleId": "R30",
    "pass": false,
    "severity": "blocking",
    "evidence": "spine.md's metaphor registry requires two honesty disclosures as page callouts: 'the numbers in this session are chosen for readability' (beat-02) and 'real embeddings live in hundreds of dimensions... nothing in the mechanism changes with dimension count' (beat-03). doc/lesson.md contains both as explicit blockquotes, but the built page text has neither anywhere. As shipped, the page lets the toy 2D integers and the two-dimensional picture stand unqualified, which is exactly the false, un-taught-later simplification R30 forbids (a learner has no signal that real embeddings are neither small, round, nor two-dimensional).",
    "suggestion": "Port the two 'Honest edges' blockquotes from lesson.md into the built page at the same beats: after the sweep in 'What happens when you turn the probe?' and after the naming in 'What did we just build?', so the compromises are disclosed in the artifact that actually ships."
  },
  {
    "ruleId": "R10",
    "pass": false,
    "severity": "advisory",
    "evidence": "The concrete stage (beat-01's two columns of numbers, lit up entry by entry) never visually becomes the schematic stage (beat-02's probe/candidate arrows) - the script has the arrows simply 'appear' as a fresh scene rather than the columns morphing into them. Likewise the symbolic stage in beat-03 adds the 'a . b' glyph as a small annotation sitting beside the score readout rather than the meter dial itself folding into the notation, so the diagram-to-notation fade is asserted by narration ('so say it plainly') rather than shown.",
    "suggestion": "Have each paired number-stack from beat-01 rotate/collapse into the corresponding arrow at the start of beat-02, and let the meter dial reshape into the a.b glyph at the beat-03 true-up instead of placing the glyph alongside it."
  },
  {
    "ruleId": "R23",
    "pass": false,
    "severity": "advisory",
    "evidence": "beat-03 recaps the three probe positions (along climbs, across dies to zero, against goes negative) with the components properly brought adjacent, but then the narrator states the aha outright ('So say it plainly: the dot product is a similarity meter') with no call-it moment inviting the learner to supply or complete the name themselves before the mint true-up confirms it. The connection is engineered up to the recap but the final naming is fully narrated rather than made by, or one step from, the learner.",
    "suggestion": "Insert a beat before the naming, e.g. 'before we call it anything, what would you call a dial that reads agree, ignore, oppose', so the learner completes or predicts the name before the mint true-up confirms it."
  }
]

